Amazon Could Soon Start Streaming Live Sports On Prime: NFL, NBA And MLB Reportedly In Sight 23 November 2016, 9:45 am EST By Alexandra Burlacu Tech Times Internet In A Minute Now Playing Amazon has reportedly been in talks with the NBA, NFL, MLB and various media networks over the rights to stream live sports online on Prime. The company is reportedly looking to bring Prime Tickets in the U.S. as well. ( Brian Ach | Getty Images ) Advertisement 
Amazon is reportedly looking to stream live sports through Prime, and it's already in talks to make it happen, according to the Wall Street Journal. 
Aiming to be a one-stop shop for all you need, from shopping to getting information or performing tasks via Alexa , to watching live sports on Prime, Amazon is apparently pushing through with another ambitious endeavor. 
The WSJ reports that Amazon has been in talks with several major sports organizations in the United States, including the National Basketball Association (NBA), National Football League (NFL), and Major League Baseball (MLB). The company has also been in talks with a number of media networks broadcasting sports, trying to obtain the rights to livestream games online. Amazon Prime Premium Sports Package 
The report reveals that Amazon has been negotiating some sort of premium sports package to offer with its Prime subscription service. Amazon Prime already offers on-demand movies and TV shows to its subscribers, but diving into live sports streaming would give it a significant edge over rival Netflix. 
If Amazon does manage to score the rights to livestream games from various sports and leagues, especially high-profile ones, it could help it get ahead of the competition and establish itself as a force in the on-demand video streaming space. At the same time, it would also pose a serious threat to traditional TV and cable companies, especially with cord-cutting on the rise. Amazon Prime Tickets Hitting U.S. Too 
A separate report from Re/code, meanwhile, reveals that Amazon plans to expand its online ticketing business to the United States. The company launched Amazon Tickets last year in the UK and is reportedly looking to offer similar services across the pond as well, planning to integrate online ticket sales into its Amazon Prime service. 
The company recently posted a number of job listings to bring Prime Tickets to the U.S. market, but no further details are available at this point. Moreover, Amazon doesn't have its eyes set just on the U.S. It's apparently looking to expand its online ticketing business globally, with Europe and Asia in the cards. 
Amazon is yet to make an official announcement regarding its plan to stream live sports or launch Prime Tickets stateside, but such moves would not be surprising.

posts.title: Amazon blocks Trump fans’ campaign to negatively rate Megyn Kelly’s book
posts.text:
Tweet 
Amazon has removed some negative reviews of Megyn Kelly’s new book, Settle For More , from their website. Kelly’s tell-all book was released on November 15th and details her experience with President-elect Trump throughout the campaign season, as well as her battle with former Fox News executive Roger Ailes. 
Shortly after the book was released, Kelly received an onslaught of negative reviews that were traced back to users of the website Reddit, specifically the Trump supporter forum called “The_Donald.” At one point in time, up to 76% of the reviews were one-star reviews, USA Today reported . 
As of early Wednesday, only 17% of the reviews written on the site were still one-star reviews, and some Amazon reviewers noticed the difference right away. USA Today detailed some of the negative responses after Amazon took down the blatantly negative reviews: 
Some commenters picked up on the removal of the negative reviews. “Tim from MD.,” for example, wrote a post titled “Over 120 1 star reviews have been deleted. Are we living in a free country anymore?” 
“Trump is president, but she wrote the book certain Clinton would win,” Tim from MD. wrote. “Now the book and her shows advertisers are getting boycotted. So apparently her attorneys have called to get negative reviews deleted. And they succeeded. I’m shocked.” 
Brianna wrote, “I have written many thoughtful reviews as to why this book is horrible! They have all been removed even though I am a reputable Amazon customer/reviewer which is why originally Megyn had the true rating of one and a half stars and now four and a half FIXED STARS!” 
Amazon did not remove all negative reviews, however, only focusing on ones that only mentioned Kelly’s “dislike” of Trump, or negative reviews with only a few words without elaboration. 
Kelly’s publisher, Harper Collins told the L.A. Times that the negative reviews had “the hallmarks of an orchestrated effort to discredit the book and our author Megyn Kelly,” and added, “We have brought it to the attention of Amazon.”

posts.title: 35 Days Of Deals: Amazon Just Turned Black Friday Into Black Month
posts.text: [caption id="attachment_086a6dd4d4cc40bba37522e098e16abf" align="" width="960"] Amazon CEO Jeff Bezos demonstrates the new Amazon Fire Phone, Wednesday, June 18, 2014, in Seattle. (AP Photo/Ted S. Warren)[/caption]In the past, Black Friday has been just that. A day. One day where you could hop online or run to your favorite store and score some serious deals. But if retailers like Amazon have anything to do about it, that way of operating could go the way of most commercial fruitcakes and get trashed. Amazon’s Push To Make Every Day Black Friday Amazon began 35 straight days of “Black Friday” bargains this week, meaning that shoppers can get some rock-bottom prices for a decent amount of time before and after Thanksgiving. The company claims it will offer a new deal up to every five minutes from now until Dec. 22, with some of the best opportunities delivered during “Turkey Five”, the five days between Thanksgiving and Cyber Monday. Some of the best deals will be on toys, electronics and fashion items, and outlined here by BusinessWire . And Amazon isn’t alone in spreading out its bargains. Macy’s, for instance, started offering “ preview doorbusters ” on Nov. 17, as did eBay . Walmart reportedly has been offering deals since Nov. 4, and Target is offering various shipping, coupons, gift cards and Cartwheel savings through December. What’s Behind The Early Sales? Retailers have good reason to extend their sales and give into Christmas creep. ShippingEasy’s 2016 Holiday Shopping Guide asserts that, in 2015, 56.6% of consumers already had started their holiday buying by early November. The National Retail Federation puts that number lower at 41.5%, but it also reports that, for the 2015 season, about 40% of shoppers had started looking for gifts by Halloween. What’s more, the number of people shopping by Halloween has been stable for the past 14 years.What’s driving people to shop early isn’t completely clear, but a Time article by Kit Yarrow offers some possibilities. Some individuals admit they’re hitting stores early out of convenience, hoping to pick things up when they don’t have to make extra trips or fight crowds. The desire to spread out the expense of the holidays for budget reasons might also be a contributing factor. Some people might want more time to ensure that they’re not stuck giving poorer quality or less-than-meaningful items to those they care about. Lastly, shoppers might hit sales as soon as they can because they can spend more time during the holidays with their loved ones. Regardless of the psychological motivations, the ability to shop more retailers anytime, anywhere due to technology and e-commerce likely has changed the ball game, too, making more people less willing to wait.But not everybody’s on board with turning the final months of the year into one giant sale blob. Many consumers feel that the degree of Christmas creep has reached outrageous levels , and there are a fair share of retailers who agree. Stores like Nordstrom, Office Depot, REI, and TJ Maxx all are pushing back, committing to staying closed on Thanksgiving Day.Whether you opt to shop early for Black Friday is completely up to you. But as a consumer, you should know that many major retailers are responding to data that shows that a big percentage of buyers don’t want to—and simply won’t—wait to start purchasing holiday gifts. That means you have the option of getting out there and shelling out your cash if you like. And when you have a choice, you can feel much more in control and, subsequently, less stressed. That’s probably not a bad thing during a time when you are supposed to relax, connect with yourself and others and give thanks.

posts.text:
News, analysis, and actionable investing ideas. Search Tech Trader Daily2 November 23, 2016, 1:02 P.M. ET Amazon AWS Price Cuts to Reduce 2017 Revenue, Profit Slightly, Says Evercore ISI By Tiernan Ray 
In case you missed it, Amazon.com ( AMZN ) yesterday announced another one of its cuts in price for its AWS cloud computing service, in this case, the price for its “ S3 ” storage offering. 
The company cut prices in most regions it served, it said in a post on AWS , and also consolidated six “pricing tiers” into just three. 
Evercore ISI ’s Ken Sena , who rates the stock a Buy and has a $990 price target, notes that this latest cut comes just after the company “cut pricing on several EC2 instances by 5-25% in numerous regions last week.” 
This is going to cut Amazon’s revenue growth rate, he thinks, but by how much is a tricky matter. Sena reasons it’s not as bad as might at first seem: At first blush, by applying the pricing cuts across our estimate for IaaS revenues (81% of total), it yields an 8.6% AWS revenue growth impact. But we think this is two aggressive as it essentially gives little credit to other AWS services, including Compute (besides EC2), Storage/CDN (besides S3), Database, Networking, Developer Tools, Management Tools, Security, Analytics, Application Services, and Mobile Services. Conversely, while optimistic, if we evenly distribute these services and apply the reduction to just one in ten, we arrive at a much more manageable 2.8% impact to AWS revenues. In reality, we believe the answer lies somewhere in the middle, leading us to estimate a ~6% impact at the midpoint. 
He ends up cutting his Amazon AWS revenue outlook for 2017, and for profit, but bear in mind there’s still some “elasticity” in the business to account for: While we suspect that these price cuts may have been factored already in Amazon’s 4Q guidance (which was issued less than a month ago), we are electing to lower our 4Q AWS revenue 1% to $3.71bn (54% y/y), a 200bp impact to growth, since the pricing changes will be in effect for just one month. This leaves Amazon total revenues effectively unchanged, given that AWS only represents 8% of revenues, albeit ~50% of CSOI. In turn, we are reducing our CSOI 2% to $2.02bn (16% y/y, 4.5% of revenue), which moves us to $1.16bn in GAAP EBIT, now slightly below the high end of the company’s guidance range. As we look to the impact of these cuts on 2017, where a full-year of cuts get factored, we are lowering our 2017 AWS revenue 2% to $17.76bn (43% y/y), or a ~350 bp impact to growth as we contemplate some elasticity, which flows through to a 4% reduction to CSOI, assuming the lost revenue represented 100% margin. 
Amazon shares today are down $6.51, or 0.8%, at $778.82.

Behind the scenes of Amazon's Black Friday and Cyber Monday sales By Komando Staff, Komando.com Julie Clopper / Shutterstock.com 
It's that time of year again! Black Friday is around the corner and you know what that means - shopping season has begun! 
As usual, the busiest places during this season will be the online shopping giant Amazon's sorting and fulfillment centers. These centers located worldwide are said to process more than a billion packages each year. 
Here's a sneak peek of these facilities leading to the hustle and bustle of Black Friday and Cyber Monday shopping fever. Photo Credit: Simon Dawson/Bloomberg 
According to its 2015 annual report, in North America alone, Amazon leases or owns about 71,655 square feet of warehouse space. 
Although the company does not publish information about its fulfillment centers, research firm Piper Jaffray reports that they had 96 U.S. warehouses in 2015 and that number is expected to be bigger by now. Photo Credit: Simon Dawson/Bloomberg

Live Sports May Be Next Big Thing For Amazon Prime Image courtesy of flaimo Looking for deals amazon streaming services tv sports Live Games Prime Services 
Amazon Prime members could soon be getting more bang for their buck when it comes to entertainment, as the e-commerce giant is rumored to be in talks with major sports leagues and television networks to offer live-streaming of sporting events. 
The Wall Street Journal , citing people familiar with the matter, reports that Amazon has been in talks with the NBA, MLB, and NFL — as well as smaller leagues for soccer and lacrosse — to obtain rights to stream live games as part of its $99/year Prime subscription service or as an add-on service. 
One of the major roadblocks is that many of the rights involved with carrying live sports are already locked up with broadcasters and the leagues each have their own lucrative out-of-market streaming services they sell through pay-TV providers. The biggest prize in streaming sports — NFL Sunday Ticket — is exclusive to AT&T/DirecTV well into the next decade . 
In the meantime, sources say the company is also talking directly with traditional TV networks about game rights they have but aren’t actually using. For example, those in the know say Amazon has approached Univision Communication about producing and packaging Mexican soccer league games that don’t air. 
Another route the company is taking reportedly involves approaching global leagues, such as Indian Premier League cricket or Russian hockey. This option, the sources say, could give Amazon a toe in the door when it comes to sports, and the ability to tailor service to customers, thus creating a better return on investment. 
The WSJ reports that while Amazon isn’t the first company to pursue streaming live games, if it is successful in the venture it could be the first significant interruption of traditional pay TV’s bread-and-butter. 
A senior sports executive tells the WSJ that Amazon’s plan could work, as the company appears to be focused on the “long game, while near-term financial returns drive the agenda for most companies.”

If you’ve never thought about playing “competitive” Fruit Ninja, this might eventually change your mind. The simple but fun (and sometimes challenging) fruit slashing game will be introducing a new variant to its collection: the Tournament Edition. Halfbrick Studios will be unveiling this new game at Amazon’s Champions of Fire e-sports tournament next week, but you can also sign up to try out the closed beta mode, in case you’re hungering to show off your fruit slashing skills. 
The Fruit Ninja Tournament Edition is actually Halfbrick Studio’s first entry into the burgeoning casual PvP / e-sport scene. At this point, not much has been revealed as to what will differentiate this game from the regular Fruit Ninja one, aside from the fact that you will be competing with other players to see who’s the best fruit slasher of all time. The game will be included in the upcoming Champions of Fire competition happening this December 2 in Las Vegas (of course, where else?) 
If you don’t know what Champions of Fire is, it is actually the Amazon Appstore’s first mobile game eSports tournament. They have invited 16 of the biggest celebrity video game streamers (yes, they’re a thing if you didn’t know yet) and they will be playing some of the most popular casual mobile games, and doing it competitively. And yes, there is an actual cash prize of $100,000 for the one who will come out on top. 
But if you’re not one of the 16 who will be playing Fruit Ninja Tournament for the first time, you can play the beta version of the game and give your feedback as well. You can sign up at the closed beta website, beta.fruitninja.com.
